00:50:59.210 --> 00:51:01.561
probably.

00:51:01.561 --> 00:51:04.060
JASON GESSNER: Does having 19
of them help you write faster?

00:51:04.060 --> 00:51:04.900
MARY ROBINETTE KOWAL:
You know, it is--

00:51:04.900 --> 00:51:05.960
no.

00:51:05.960 --> 00:51:08.050
But I will actually
bring out the typewriter

00:51:08.050 --> 00:51:10.300
to write sometimes
because it changes

00:51:10.300 --> 00:51:11.770
the rhythms with
which you write,

00:51:11.770 --> 00:51:14.380
and there are times
when just changing

00:51:14.380 --> 00:51:17.020
the medium of communication is
enough to shake a story idea

00:51:17.020 --> 00:51:21.190
loose or you want that rhythm.

00:51:21.190 --> 00:51:22.630
Because with a
manual typewriter,

00:51:22.630 --> 00:51:24.040
because you have to
hit the carriage return

00:51:24.040 --> 00:51:25.420
at the end of each
line, there's a moment

00:51:25.420 --> 00:51:27.370
where you're doing
a little composition

00:51:27.370 --> 00:51:28.510
at the end of each line.

00:51:28.510 --> 00:51:30.010
And then, when you have
to change the paper,

00:51:30.010 --> 00:51:31.610
there's another
moment of composition.

00:51:31.610 --> 00:51:33.976
So it does completely
change the way I write.

00:51:33.976 --> 00:51:34.906
Yeah.

00:51:34.906 --> 00:51:37.030
AUDIENCE: I saw you at the
