00:51:56.560 --> 00:51:59.110
MARY ROBINETTE KOWAL: All right.

00:51:59.110 --> 00:52:00.650
Some of this is
me extrapolating,

00:52:00.650 --> 00:52:03.440
so let's be clear.

00:52:03.440 --> 00:52:06.802
So one of the interesting
things about computer voices

00:52:06.802 --> 00:52:09.010
in the United States is that
they tend, by and large,

00:52:09.010 --> 00:52:11.240
to be women.

00:52:11.240 --> 00:52:18.620
And we know that the
people with Siri and Alexa

00:52:18.620 --> 00:52:20.210
and these other
things, the people

00:52:20.210 --> 00:52:22.430
have said very specifically
that they were thinking

00:52:22.430 --> 00:52:25.520
about the computer
on "Star Trek"

00:52:25.520 --> 00:52:27.290
when they assigned
the female voice

00:52:27.290 --> 00:52:29.150
and when they were
thinking about it.

00:52:29.150 --> 00:52:35.520
What's interesting is that "Star
Trek," California, JPL, Jet

00:52:35.520 --> 00:52:38.030
Propulsion Laboratory-- so
if you're doing research

00:52:38.030 --> 00:52:40.820
on space travel,
JPL is the closest

00:52:40.820 --> 00:52:43.370
place that you're going to be
able to go when "Star Trek" was

00:52:43.370 --> 00:52:44.480
coming out.

00:52:44.480 --> 00:52:47.450
JPL had a policy
that the only people

00:52:47.450 --> 00:52:49.640
they hired for the computer
department were women.

00:52:49.640 --> 00:52:54.970
They did not hire
men as a policy,

00:52:54.970 --> 00:52:57.780
and from early, early days.

00:52:57.780 --> 00:53:00.479
So the computer voices--

00:53:00.479 --> 00:53:02.520
so that means that you've
got this roomful of men

00:53:02.520 --> 00:53:05.490
at a launch, and
someone will say,

00:53:05.490 --> 00:53:07.000
computer, give us the velocity.

00:53:07.000 --> 00:53:11.430
And this one lone woman's
voice will come out and answer.

00:53:11.430 --> 00:53:15.660
When you look at Germany,
their computer voices

00:53:15.660 --> 00:53:17.680
tend to be male.

00:53:17.680 --> 00:53:20.200
When you look at their
early space program,

00:53:20.200 --> 00:53:23.430
their computers
tended to be men.

00:53:23.430 --> 00:53:25.230
Now, I don't know
that there is--

00:53:25.230 --> 00:53:28.110
I mean, I have correlation,
which is not the same as

00:53:28.110 --> 00:53:30.270
causation, but there
certainly seems

00:53:30.270 --> 00:53:31.770
to be a pattern
there where it looks

00:53:31.770 --> 00:53:38.580
very much like art imitating
life, imitating art again.

00:53:38.580 --> 00:53:42.470
So I find this back and
forth really fascinating.

