00:54:12.430 --> 00:54:15.200
to pick as a research project?

00:54:15.200 --> 00:54:17.150
MARY ROBINETTE KOWAL:
So it's interesting.

00:54:17.150 --> 00:54:18.566
One of the things
that you make me

00:54:18.566 --> 00:54:22.270
think about when you ask that
is that when I was researching

00:54:22.270 --> 00:54:25.090
this, I watched a number
of episodes of "Mr. Wizard"

00:54:25.090 --> 00:54:27.190
from the 1950s.

00:54:27.190 --> 00:54:29.050
And then, I also
wound up watching

00:54:29.050 --> 00:54:34.190
some of the reboot, the
later reboot from the 70s,

00:54:34.190 --> 00:54:36.516
and there was one
in the 80s, as well.

00:54:36.516 --> 00:54:38.890
And the interesting thing is
that the one in the 80s, all

00:54:38.890 --> 00:54:40.848
of the science that
they're having the girls do

00:54:40.848 --> 00:54:41.860
is very gendered.

00:54:41.860 --> 00:54:45.190
It's like, let's see about
the science of lipstick.

00:54:45.190 --> 00:54:46.000
I'm not kidding.

00:54:46.000 --> 00:54:47.500
I don't think that
was "Mr. Wizard,"

00:54:47.500 --> 00:54:50.110
but I have actually seen the
science of lipstick, and again,

00:54:50.110 --> 00:54:52.450
very stabby.

00:54:52.450 --> 00:54:55.900
The 1950s one is
not gendered at all.

00:54:55.900 --> 00:54:59.140
The little girls are in skirts,
absolutely, but they're like,

00:54:59.140 --> 00:55:02.260
let's look at thermodynamics.

00:55:02.260 --> 00:55:05.060
Let's look at how
we create batteries.

00:55:05.060 --> 00:55:07.600
He speaks to them and
addresses them exactly

00:55:07.600 --> 00:55:09.550
as he would little boys.

00:55:09.550 --> 00:55:14.660
So in terms of spaceflight, I
think space is a great topic.

00:55:18.100 --> 00:55:23.354
In terms of something that
is specifically about women,

00:55:23.354 --> 00:55:24.770
one of the things
that I would say

00:55:24.770 --> 00:55:28.735
is have them look at the
early aviation pioneers.

00:55:31.330 --> 00:55:33.880
Her name is not in
my head right now,

00:55:33.880 --> 00:55:41.260
but does anyone want to make
a guess about what year--

00:55:41.260 --> 00:55:46.922
so first of all, the first
professional aeronaut, and that

00:55:46.922 --> 00:55:48.380
should give you a
clue right there.

00:55:48.380 --> 00:55:52.110
The first professional
aeronaut was a woman.

00:55:52.110 --> 00:55:56.120
Does anyone want to guess
about what year this was?

00:55:56.120 --> 00:55:59.170
1811.

00:55:59.170 --> 00:55:59.860
Right?

00:55:59.860 --> 00:56:00.940
1811.

00:56:00.940 --> 00:56:04.891
This woman was employed by
Napoleon for her ballooning

00:56:04.891 --> 00:56:05.390
skills.

00:56:08.290 --> 00:56:10.965
So I would say--

00:56:10.965 --> 00:56:12.340
I wish I could
remember her name.

00:56:12.340 --> 00:56:14.080
I would also say look
at Bessie Coleman.

00:56:14.080 --> 00:56:18.600
Bessie Coleman was the first
African-American woman pilot.

00:56:18.600 --> 00:56:21.356
It was not legal for her to be
a pilot in the United States.

00:56:21.356 --> 00:56:22.480
She couldn't get a license.

00:56:22.480 --> 00:56:28.780
And this is in, I want
to say, 1911, 1912.

00:56:28.780 --> 00:56:31.210
Very, very early.

00:56:31.210 --> 00:56:36.160
So the only place she could get
a license to fly was in Paris.

00:56:36.160 --> 00:56:40.740
So she taught herself
French, went to France,

00:56:40.740 --> 00:56:45.120
got the pilot's
license, came back.

00:56:45.120 --> 00:56:49.890
So looking at the
early pioneers--

00:56:49.890 --> 00:56:52.911
I think that they are the ones
who often are most written out

00:56:52.911 --> 00:56:55.410
of history because we've had
the most time to write them out

00:56:55.410 --> 00:56:58.020
of history.

00:56:58.020 --> 00:56:59.760
So I would look at those.

00:56:59.760 --> 00:57:02.100
There's a great book
called "Black Wings," which

00:57:02.100 --> 00:57:06.150
is about African-American
aviation, that

00:57:06.150 --> 00:57:08.880
talks about Bessie Coleman.

00:57:08.880 --> 00:57:11.550
I would also say
"Promise to the Moon,"

00:57:11.550 --> 00:57:15.180
which is the story of
the Mercury 13 women.

00:57:15.180 --> 00:57:17.670
There's a good
documentary about them.

00:57:17.670 --> 00:57:19.860
So mercury 13 is also--

00:57:19.860 --> 00:57:22.920
what would space look
like if that program

00:57:22.920 --> 00:57:24.090
hadn't been shut down?

00:57:24.090 --> 00:57:27.660
I think about this all the time.

00:57:27.660 --> 00:57:30.300
AUDIENCE: I'm interested in
