00:57:30.300 --> 00:57:32.982
between "Calculating Sky" and--

00:57:32.982 --> 00:57:34.690
MARY ROBINETTE KOWAL:
"Calculating Stars"

00:57:34.690 --> 00:57:34.880
and "Fated Sky."

00:57:34.880 --> 00:57:36.000
AUDIENCE: "Calculating
Stars" and "Fated Sky,"

00:57:36.000 --> 00:57:38.166
which were only three months
apart in release dates.

00:57:38.166 --> 00:57:41.430
MARY ROBINETTE KOWAL:
Not even three months.

00:57:41.430 --> 00:57:43.552
AUDIENCE: My wife just
read Maureen Johnson's most

00:57:43.552 --> 00:57:46.010
recent book, only to discover
that it's really half a book,

00:57:46.010 --> 00:57:47.384
and that the rest
of the thriller

00:57:47.384 --> 00:57:49.600
is still not yet to be released.

00:57:49.600 --> 00:57:52.020
What was your sort
of thought process

00:57:52.020 --> 00:57:55.290
behind let's get that
out in this time frame

00:57:55.290 --> 00:57:58.587
and not wait six
months or whatever?

00:57:58.587 --> 00:58:00.420
MARY ROBINETTE KOWAL:
So "Calculating Stars"

00:58:00.420 --> 00:58:01.680
came out July 3rd.

00:58:01.680 --> 00:58:06.600
"Fated Sky" came out August
21st, which is very fast.

00:58:06.600 --> 00:58:09.240
My basic thought process on
that was that my publisher said,

00:58:09.240 --> 00:58:10.573
would you like to do this thing?

00:58:10.573 --> 00:58:12.990
And I said, yes, I would
like to do that thing.

00:58:12.990 --> 00:58:19.286
The reason that this is an
interesting publishing strategy

00:58:19.286 --> 00:58:21.660
to try when you have an author
who can turn two books out

00:58:21.660 --> 00:58:23.370
that fast--

00:58:23.370 --> 00:58:25.000
I wrote the second
book in six months,

00:58:25.000 --> 00:58:30.020
which is very fast for
hard science fiction.

00:58:30.020 --> 00:58:34.790
The reason is because
there is a known phenomenon

00:58:34.790 --> 00:58:37.820
that when the first book
in a series comes out,

00:58:37.820 --> 00:58:40.790
there's a bump.

00:58:40.790 --> 00:58:44.310
There's something we call
the series death spiral.

00:58:44.310 --> 00:58:48.410
So the fifth book in my
series did not sell as well as

00:58:48.410 --> 00:58:50.970
the first book by a lot.

00:58:50.970 --> 00:58:53.880
But the moment I have a book
come out in a new series,

00:58:53.880 --> 00:58:56.540
there's a bump,
and we know that.

00:58:56.540 --> 00:58:58.740
So you want you want
new books coming out.

00:58:58.740 --> 00:59:01.710
And then we also know that a
lot of people are completists.

00:59:01.710 --> 00:59:04.080
They will wait until an
entire series is finished

00:59:04.080 --> 00:59:06.590
before they buy any of them.

00:59:06.590 --> 00:59:08.980
And then, when the
last book comes out,

00:59:08.980 --> 00:59:12.600
there's a bump in the
sales of the first book.

00:59:12.600 --> 00:59:15.930
So if you can get both
of them coming out

00:59:15.930 --> 00:59:18.120
within about a
month of each other,

00:59:18.120 --> 00:59:21.750
you have both of those phenomena
happening at the same time,

00:59:21.750 --> 00:59:25.450
and the book sells
significantly better.

00:59:25.450 --> 00:59:27.450
So that's basically--
that was the experiment

00:59:27.450 --> 00:59:28.650
that they wanted to try.

00:59:28.650 --> 00:59:29.860
And it has worked.

00:59:29.860 --> 00:59:33.900
Like, when I look at the
diagram of my book sales,

00:59:33.900 --> 00:59:36.750
it's like, these books
are doing very nicely.

00:59:36.750 --> 00:59:40.380
And then, "Calculating Stars"
happens, and it's way up here.

00:59:40.380 --> 00:59:42.259
So it definitely worked.

00:59:42.259 --> 00:59:43.800
There's also a number
of other things

00:59:43.800 --> 00:59:45.674
that are happening with
"Calculating Stars"--

00:59:45.674 --> 00:59:47.790
bringing out a space
book the same year

00:59:47.790 --> 00:59:53.130
as the 60th anniversary of
NASA and, the year before,

00:59:53.130 --> 00:59:55.320
the 50th anniversary of Apollo.

00:59:55.320 --> 00:59:58.290
There's a lot of--

00:59:58.290 --> 00:59:59.550
the timing is good.

00:59:59.550 --> 01:00:01.437
I hit "Zeitgeist," as well.

01:00:01.437 --> 01:00:03.270
But that's why they
wanted to bring them out

01:00:03.270 --> 01:00:04.494
back to back like that.

01:00:04.494 --> 01:00:05.910
JASON GESSNER: And
as a reader, it

01:00:05.910 --> 01:00:09.012
